<HEAD>Fair Skies Over Much of the Nation, Chill in the East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Fair weather prevailed today over much of the United States,
with rain in parts of the nation's midsection and chilly
temperatures in the East.
   Rain fell in Kansas City, St. Louis, Rapid City, S.D., and North
Platte, Neb.
   Morning fog settled over Omaha and Los Angeles and skies were
cloudy in portions of the West and Northeast, including San Diego
and Pittsburgh.
   North-central Kansas received snow Thursday, while a
thunderstorm accompanied by hail up to a half-inch in diameter and
winds gusting to 40 mph hit Casper, Wyo.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered Thursday over the
northern Rockies and central Plains, while snow fell on western New
York state and western Pennsylvania.
   A high Thursday of 91 degrees in Las Vegas broke the city's
record for the date, 89 degrees in 1988.
   The high temperature Thursday in the Lower 48 states was 103
degrees in Borrego Springs and Palm Springs in California.
   Other reports at 3 a.m. EDT:
   _East: Albany, N.Y. 26 fair; Atlanta 45 fair; Boston 33 fair;
Buffalo 33 fair; Charleston, S.C. 47 fair; Chattanooga 39 fair;
Cincinnati 33 fair; Cleveland 27 fair; Detroit 30 partly cloudy;
Hatteras 41 fair; Jacksonville 43 fair; Key West 73 fair; Knoxville
37 fair; Macon 38 fair; Miami 65 fair; New York 37 fair;
Philadelphia 33 fair; Pittsburgh 32 cloudy; Portland, Maine 30
fair; Richmond 36 fair; Tampa 57 fair; Washington, D.C. 37 fair.
   _Central: Birmingham 38 fair; Bismarck 25 fair; Chicago 34 fair;
